data.message: A new elevation map created from New Horizons spacecraft data shows Pluto’s “sunken heart”. The vast expanse of the icy surface is on average 2 miles lower than the surrounding terrain. Take a look: http://go.nasa.gov/1VGlOPQ

After painting our new knock-down plaster finish on our living room ceiling this afternoon, I got on FB and started scrolling down. This photo popped-up and my first thought? Someone took a photo of our newly plastered living room ceiling. :D
It did cross my mind Jenni, but then I am not viewing this as a scientist!
Sorry Jenni, got to add who did your plastering, in my view you should sack him! lol
Your hillarios.!
same thing I thought lol
Nature Imitates Art.
Your lucky it looks like Pluto. It could have been Uranus.
Hahah
Lol degenerite writing you did on your own, so aim for another afterlife off this real planet lol

If the surface is lower that the rest of the planet... wouldn't that seem evidence that the surface was 'scrapped off' by a glancing contact with another large body? (Charon comes to mind for some reason)  I wish NASA only knew.  ✨
They don't reply on social media.
Michael, Thanks kind Sir.
Michael Davis, actually, they have before.
then there is hope in the world  :D

No that's likely not what caused this depression. even "glancing" impacts like you describe carry a tremendous amount of kinetic energy with them due to the size of the masses involved. Besides, there's never a "near miss" when it comes to colliding bodies, usually the tidal forces are significant enough to cause the smaller body to break up when coming to close to the planet. (called the Roche limit.)

depressions of this sort, I would guess, would be created either by an meteorite, or could be in this case the result of sub-glacial tectonic forces or maybe subsidence and liquid upwelling which retextured the surface.

Is density and buoyancy relevant? I mean every less dense material is buoyant in every more dense material - could that be a factor here?

I wonder if there's a connection between buoyancy, density, and gravity? Well the last two have a pretty well known connection, and I'm not too well informed on how buoyancy works, other than the heavier stuff goes down and the lighter stuff goes up, but in order to learn more about gravity, it might be possible to study density and buoyancy.

I'd love to learn more about buoyancy too, along with noting that most of our 'stuff' is pretty low #'d on the periodic table...wouldn't it be neat if there was a class of 'lighter' materials with fractions or even negative numbers for their atomic weight?

I could probably learn a bit more chemistry too, maybe I'll grab a book off amazon...
Yeah :\
Great, you got commented on by a bot troll lol
The atomic weight is a count of protons in its nucleus.  Most of our solar system contains the same materials from creation of the system.
I thought it might be neat to discuss buoyancy and its relevancy, as it might make an interesting and insightful discussion, along with spreading awareness of the idea.

The relationship of buoyancy and gravity is well known.  Without gravity there is no buoyancy.  And there is a really good article that explains how the ice plains formed it was released in January.  Buoyancy has little to do with the formation of the plains but the floating bergs on the plains are a perfect example of it.
I've been pondering if it might be possible to construct lighter weight and other atoms using quarks or other materials that compose the elements of atoms?
It doesn't get much lighter than hydrogen.  One of proton, one electron.
Maybe a deposit of a core material pooled there, like cool lava or a glacier, and was shed, sloughed, into space.
Can't we drop a bomb there and blast it open so we can see what sort of minerals there are. Diamonds or gold or silver so on. Very curious.

bombs cant explode in space like they do on earth even if we dropped hundreds i dont think it would have much of an impact on the planet,instead of researching the furthest planets we should research the closest ones, extract resources and bring them on earth to research them and further improve space technology,wait why do i even.. blah blah blah

It would be a hot news in all newspapers and TV for a month. If it didn't happened - the answer is NO :)
Thanks for the reply. I've watch some of their videos about mars but they never mentioned anything about what they've collected. Thanks 😊
Interesting, can you tell us all how hydrogen and oxygen got to be on pluto to form Ice when trees make oxygen? No trees on Pluto.
What?  Trees produce oxygen as a by product when they take in CO2, they don't make it.  Oxygen is a naturally occurring element.  There are tons of celestial bodies that contain water.
No water on the moon, no water on mars, no trees either.

Noel Constable, there's no trees on Enceladus, but the little moon has lots of water. Water is simply the result of combining 2 hydrogen atoms and 1 oxygen atom. There's countless molecules with both elements, too. H2O2 is the first that comes to mind, which is hydrogen peroxide.

My apologies I shouldn't have put genius stuff up here, thank you Ian Rogerson and Mel Quin for your tips. I'm fully aware of the composition of water. On oxygen being abundant I can only say to ask NASA why their astronauts wear their spacesuits and bubble helments whilst space walking at ISS and the moon. Why did the scramjet engine they have in their X space rockets fall out of the sky when it reached oxygen deprivation altitude. I'm going to unlike the Nasa site now thanks for the convo.
If water is present that doesn't mean oxygen is in the air.  In most places it is either in the form of ice or below the surface.

Trees do not make the element oxygen. They split h2o into hydrogen and oxygen. Trees do not fuse hydrogen into oxygen like stars do. There is lots of water in the outer solar system. Much much more than on EARTH.
So NASA is Pluto a planet or not? If not, why the research?

New Horizons took 9 years to get there once launched and many more of planning and construction. It was only during that time that the definitions of planets and dwarf planets were set following the discovery of other similar objects like Ceres, makemake and Eris etc.
Just because it isnt a planet doesnt make it not interesting to explore.
NASA didn't downgrade Pluto nor create the new dwarf planet category.
its always been a planet

Nasa didn't downgrade Pluto and it a dwarf planet because it cannot clear its orbital path. Also, the moon is larger than Pluto. Elevating it to planet status also means that a number of asteroids also need to be elevated to planet status
its heart sunk when they said she was no longer a planet..
I agree Awesome comment thanks
You mean "when it finally joined its brothers and sisters"?
